1. Overview

   This module contains rdn (railway dedicated network) related functions
   for an IMS environment (S-CSCF and/or I-CSCF).

   This module is most useful for terminating unregistered services that
   are triggered by the I/S-CSCF and that are identified by hierarchical
   address ranges of E.164 addresses and of EIRENE addresses (in the
   Request-URI), not unlike wildcarded PSIs.

   By configuring these address ranges at the I/S-CSCF, one can save one
   SAR/SAA exchange with the HSS per call.

   EIRENE addresses are railway specific telephone numbers, which have
   been defined by the UIC. This explains the name of the module RDN =
   Railway Dedicated Networks.

   Additionally, this module defines kamailio transformations, which are
   tailored for the use in RDNs, e.g. for the transformation of functional
   numbers and of MCData SDS into instant messages and vice versa.

   This module is even more useful, when implementing an IWF according to
   ETSI TS 103 792, in which case some specific routing scripts will be
   needed.

   Following high level functions are provided by this module:
     * Definition of RDN Services with or without MCx AS Delivery
     *
          + rdn_services.list: EIRENE RDN Services
          + rdn_services.list: E.164 RDN Services
          + dpsi.list: Distinct PSI RDN Services
          + dpsi.list: Domain Based RDN Services
     * analyse_eirene_ruri() - search EIRENE RDN Service from $ru
     * analyse_e164_ruri() - search E.164 RDN Service from $ru
     * analyse_dpsi_ruri() - search Distinct PSI RDN Service from $ru
     * analyse_domain_ruri() - search Domain based PSI RDN Service from
       $ru
     * prepare_term_unreg(domain) - prepare service, after it has been
       found by analyse_..._ruri()
     * analyse_eirene_pvar("pv") - search EIRENE RDN Service from PV
     * analyse_e164_ruri() - search E.164 RDN Service from PV
     * analyse_dpsi_ruri() - search Distinct PSI RDN Service from PV
     * analyse_domain_ruri() - search Domain based PSI RDN Service from PV

2. Dependencies

   2.1. Kamailio Modules
   2.2. External Libraries or Applications

2.1. Kamailio Modules

   After kamailio core modules the following modules must be loaded before
   this module:
     * TM - Transaction Manager
     * ims_userloc_scscf (if used on S-CSCF)
     * ims_registrar_scscf (if used on S-CSCF)

2.2. External Libraries or Applications

   This module requires the internal IMS library.

3. Parameters

   3.1. list_file (e.g. rdn_services.list)
   3.2. dpsi_file (e.g. dpsi.list)
   3.3. cx_userdata_templates (e.g. CxUserData_tmpl.xml)
   3.4. rdn_node_type (integer)

3.1. list_file (e.g. rdn_services.list)

   This file contains the digit combinations with their respective
   application server/service key.

   Default value is 'rdn_services.list'.

   Example 1.1. list_file parameter usage
...
modparam("ims_rdn", "list_file", "/usr/etc/kamailio-scscf-ref/rdn_services.list"
)
...

rdn_services.list entry example:
...
# digits application server     sessiontype  hardcoded-RURI   DEL INSRT
0432     sip:my-as.com          first-answer sip:srvc@ims.net 3   43
+4350255 sip:my-as.com          private      sip:srvc@ims.net 0
+49      sip:my-as.com          private
...

NOTE: lets assume a Req-URI sip:043287654321@ims.net;user=gsmr is received.
      In this case the first row will apply, where hardcoded-RURI, DEL and
      INSRT are not empty.

      I.e. - we have an EIRENE RDN Service WITH MCx AS Delivery.

      Lets assume a Req-URI sip:+43502553468@ims.net;user=phone is received.
      In this case the second row will apply and we have an E.164 RDN Service
      WITH MCx AS Delivery.

      Lets assume a Req-URI sip:+49684512345@ims.net;user=phone is received.
      In this case the third row will apply and we have an E.164 RDN Service
      withOUT MCx AS Delivery (4th, 5th and 6th column are empty). The Request
      will not receive a "special MCPTT handling" by the routing configuration

NOTE: The digits field must contain digits only - kamailio server fails
      to start in case digits field contains non digit characters.

3.2. dpsi_file (e.g. dpsi.list)

   This file contains the distinct public service identifiers with their
   respective application server/sessiontype, and it contains the
   descriptions of the domain based RDN services.

   Default value is 'dpsi.list'.

   Example 1.2. dpsi_file parameter usage
...
modparam("ims_rdn", "dpsi_file", "/usr/etc/kamailio-scscf-ref/dpsi.list")
...

dpsi.list entry example:
...
# service             application server         sessiontype
 service34            sip:172.29.21.20:5060      mcptt34
 MESSAGE@ipsmgw.com   sip:172.29.21.19:5060      ipsmgw
...

NOTE: Size of hash table is currently optimized for 64 entries.

3.3. cx_userdata_templates (e.g. CxUserData_tmpl.xml)

   This file is a part of the common configuration and should only be
   changed, if you really know what you do.

   Default value is '/usr/etc/CFG_COMMON/CxUserData_tmpl.xml'.

   Example 1.3. cx_userdata_templates parameter usage
...
modparam("ims_rdn", "cx_userdata_templates", "/usr/etc/kamailio-scscf/CxUserData
_tmpl.xml")
...

3.4. rdn_node_type (integer)

   This parameter replaces the old i_am_at_icscf flag and defines the node
   type where the ims_rdn module is running.

   Depending on the value, the module will behave accordingly, especially
   in terms of database interactions, and whether certain functions such
   as prepare_fa_delivery() and prepare_term_unreg() are available, which
   are only applicable when operating as an S-CSCF.

   When using Multi-MCx Domain Support (i.e., when rdn_node_type is set to
   16 or 17), two additional columns are expected for each entry in
   rdn_services.list and dpsi.list: MCx Domain and IWF Domain. These must
   be inserted after the AS/S-CSCF FQDN and after the session type. If the
   support is not enabled (i.e., rdn_node_type < 16), these columns must
   not be present.

   Note: The optional S-CSCF flag is treated as part of the AS/S-CSCF FQDN
   field and is not counted as a separate column. Therefore, the FQDN is
   considered to be in column 3, and the session type in column 4 (unless
   MCx support or special handling shifts this further).
     * MCx domain indicates the source domain (e.g., for the originating
       UE)
     * IWF domain defines the target domain (e.g., for the terminating UE
       or IWF AS)
     * Hardcoded R-URI defines the target AS or gateway for MCx delivery

   If any of these fields are missing, the module will reject the
   configuration entry at startup and log an error such as: Cannot add RDN
   service. Special handling needs hardcoded RURI(...)

   Supported values:
     * 0 S-CSCF (default mode)
     * 1 I-CSCF
     * 16 S-CSCF with Multi MCx Domain Support
     * 17 I-CSCF with Multi MCx Domain Support

   Example 1.4. rdn_node_type parameter usage
  ...
  modparam("ims_rdn", "rdn_node_type", 1)
  ...

4. Functions

   4.1. analyse_eirene_ruri()
   4.2. analyse_e164_ruri()
   4.3. analyse_dpsi_ruri()
   4.4. analyse_domain_ruri()
   4.5. prepare_term_unreg(domain)

4.1. analyse_eirene_ruri()

   The function presumes that the user has checked, whether the Req-URI
   actually contains an EIRENE FN (e.g. by checking for the URI parameter
   "user=gsmr").

   The function searches for a contiguous block of digits in the userpart
   of the Req-URI and compares these digits with the stored digit tree of
   EIRENE RDN Services.

   If it finds a matching EIRENE RDN Service in the file
   rdn_services.list, then it stores the values from the found row in AVPs
   and returns positive.

   If it encounters a problem, e.g. if no service is found, then a
   negative result is returned.

   Negative return codes can be interpreted as follows:
     * -1 (generic error, service not found) - a generic error has
       happened or the service has not been found (e.g. Req-URI cannot be
       parsed, no matching service found for this Req-URI)
     * -2 (AVPs could not be stored) - everything went well, but at last
       the AVPs could not be stored, PVs will be incorrect

   Positive return codes can be interpreted as follows:
     * 1 (OK) - everything went well. The next action should be calling
       prepare_term_unreg() to prepare the DB for the ims_isc module
     * 2 (Mx-Delivery) - everything went well. However the hardcoded-RURI
       (4th column in the file rdn_services.list) does not contain a
       userpart, i.e. it is an FQDN (of the AS), but not a PSI. Hence the
       IMS Subscription cannot be stored to DB and calling
       prepare_term_unreg() will be useless. The routing script should
       deliver the Request to the AS via the Mx interface ("per FQDN", but
       not "per PSI")

   This function can be used in REQUEST_ROUTE only.

   Example 1.5. analyse_eirene_ruri usage
...

# Terminating

xlog("L_INFO", "Detected: this transaction is on the \"Term\" S-CSCF");

if (uri == myself || uri =~ "tel:.*") {
  if (!term_impu_registered("location")) {
    xlog("L_INFO", "user not registered -> try unreg services");
    $var(ret) = analyse_domain_ruri();
    if ($var(ret) < 0) {
      $var(ret) = (uri_param("user","gsmr") && ($rU=~"^[0-9]+$"));
      if ($var(ret)) {
        $var(ret) = analyse_eirene_ruri();
      } else {
        $var(ret)=(uri_param("user","phone") && ($rU =~ "^\+[0-9]+$")));
        if ($var(ret)) {
          $var(ret) = analyse_e164_ruri();
        } else {
          $var(ret) = analyse_dpsi_ruri();
        }
      }
    }
    if ($var(ret) < 0){
      if ($var(ret) == -2) {
        xlog("L_ERR", "found RDN service/DPSI, could not set AVP");
        sl_send_reply("500", "Server Internal Error - Cannot set AVP");
        exit;
      }
      xlog("L_INFO", "did not find RDN Service/DPSI -> try UNREG SAR");
      assign_server_unreg("UNREG_SAR_REPLY", "location", "term");
      exit;
    }
    else {
      if (!prepare_term_unreg("location")) {
        xlog("L_ERR", "found RDN service/DPSI, cannot prepare DB for sending");
        sl_send_reply("500", "Server Internal Error - Cannot prepare sending ser
vice");
        exit;
      }
      if ($var(ret) == 2) {
        xlog("L_INFO", "RDN Service has hardcoded RURI, but w/o user part");
        route(fwd);
        exit;
      }
      xlog("L_INFO", "could prepare unreg terminating service -> continue");
    }
  }
  else {
    xlog("L_INFO", "user is registered at this S-CSCF, continue");
  }
} else {
  xlog("L_INFO", "Terminating S-CSCF detects: this request is not for me");
  sl_send_reply("403","Forbidden - Domain not served");
  exit();
}
route(term);
break;
...

