4.5. prepare_term_unreg(domain)

   This function is not applicable at an I-CSCF

   The function presumes that the user has called one of the functions
   analyse_eirene_ruri(), analyse_e164_ruri(), analyse_dpsi_ruri() or
   analyse_domain_ruri() and the result was 1.

   It looks up the stored values in the AVPs and tries to update the scscf
   database with an unregistered subscription. IMS subscription data are
   prepared including application server name for routing the INVITE/
   PUBLISH/ SUBSCRIBE/ MESSAGE/ or REFER/ message to the Application
   Server. The information about the service is kept in the AVPs and can
   still be read out from the routing configuration by using the PVs
   defined by this module.

   If it encounters a problem, e.g. if the DB cannot be accessed, then a
   negative result is returned.

   Negative return codes can be interpreted as follows:
     * -1 (generic error) - a generic error has happened (e.g. Cx user
       data could not be parsed, contacts could not be updated in DB)

   Positive return codes can be interpreted as follows::
     * 1 (OK) - everything went well. The next call of
       isc_match_filter("term","location") - see the description of module
       ims_isc - will deliver the request to the AS

   Meaning of the parameters is as follows:
     * domain - Logical domain within registrar.

   This function can be used in REQUEST_ROUTE only.

   Example 1.9. prepare_term_unreg usage
...
see the example at function analyse_eirene_ruri
...

5. Exported pseudo-variables

   5.1. rdn_as_name
   5.2. rdn_scscf_name
   5.3. rdn_sessiontype
   5.4. rdn_hardcoded_ruri
   5.5. rdn_del
   5.6. rdn_insrt

5.1. rdn_as_name

   Returns the value of the 2nd column of the found row of tables
   rdn_services.list or dpsi.list, after one of the functions
   prepare_fa_delivery(), analyse_eirene_ruri(), analyse_e164_ruri(),
   analyse_dpsi_ruri() or analyse_domain_ruri() has successfully detected
   an RDN Service or a DPSI.

   This PV is used on the S-CSCF. Please refer to rdn_scscf_name for
   I-CSCF.

   Example 1.10. rdn_as_name pseudo-variable usage
...
# add Route header
$rdn_as_name
...

5.2. rdn_scscf_name

   Returns the value of the 2nd column of the found row of tables
   rdn_services.list or dpsi.list, after one of the functions
   prepare_fa_delivery(), analyse_eirene_ruri(), analyse_e164_ruri(),
   analyse_dpsi_ruri() or analyse_domain_ruri() has successfully detected
   an RDN Service or a DPSI.

   This PV is used on the I-CSCF. Please refer to rdn_as_name for S-CSCF.

   Example 1.11. rdn_scscf_name pseudo-variable usage
...
# add Route header
$rdn_scscf_name
...

5.3. rdn_sessiontype

   Returns the value of the 3rd column of the found row of tables
   rdn_services.list or dpsi.list, after one of the functions
   prepare_fa_delivery(), analyse_eirene_ruri(), analyse_e164_ruri(),
   analyse_dpsi_ruri() or analyse_domain_ruri() has successfully detected
   an RDN Service or a DPSI.

   Example 1.12. rdn_sessiontype pseudo-variable usage
...
# add sessiontype
$rdn_sessiontpye
...

5.4. rdn_hardcoded_ruri

   Returns the value of the 4th column of the found row of tables
   rdn_services.list, if it exists, after one of the functions
   prepare_fa_delivery(), analyse_eirene_ruri() or analyse_e164_ruri() has
   successfully detected an RDN Service.

   If this PV is $null or an empty string, then the 4th, 5th and 6th
   column of the found row are empty. Hence we have an "RDN Service
   WITHOUT MCx AS Delivery (no MCPTT handling necessary)

   If this PV is a string with the value "*", then the routing
   configuration SHALL NOT replace the Req-URI with the value of this PV.

   Otherwise, the routing configuration shall replace the Req-URI with
   this value, before calling isc_match_filter().

   Example 1.13. rdn_hardcoded_ruri pseudo-variable usage
...
## flexible modification of Request URI (depends on position in digit tree)
## the PVs $rdn_sessiontype, $rdn_hardcoded_ruri, $rdn_insrt and $rdn_del
## have been looked up by the function prepare_fa_delivery and can be
##  different for each RDN service
##    make an E.164 from a CT8
##    make a functional alias from a CT5
##    make a functional alias from a CT1
##    make a functional alias from a CT7
if ($rdn_sessiontype == "prearranged")
  $var(ibsipr) = "sip:g.mcptt." + $rdn_insrt + $(rU{s.substr,$rdn_del,0}) +
                 ".prearranged@" + NETWORKNAME + ";user=gsmr";
else
  $var(ibsipr) = "sip:+" + $rdn_insrt + $(rU{s.substr,$rdn_del,0}) +
                 "@" + NETWORKNAME + ";user=phone";
$ru = $rdn_hardcoded_ruri;
...

5.5. rdn_del

   Returns the value of the 5th column of the found row of the table
   rdn_services.list, after one of the functions prepare_fa_delivery(),
   analyse_eirene_ruri() or analyse_e164_ruri() has successfully detected
   an RDN Service.

   Example 1.14. rdn_del pseudo-variable usage
...
see the example above (rdn_hardcoded_ruri)
...

5.6. rdn_insrt

   Returns the value of the 6th column of the found row of the table
   rdn_services.list, after one of the functions prepare_fa_delivery(),
   analyse_eirene_ruri() or analyse_e164_ruri() has successfully detected
   an RDN Service.

   Example 1.15. rdn_insrt pseudo-variable usage
...
see the example above (rdn_hardcoded_ruri)
...
